  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus does not contain material sufficient to perform a direct comparison of the Urdu 'dast' (hand) and Old English 'hond' (hand) specifically as figures or metaphors for action and agency.**\n\nWhile the corpus includes Old English poetry (e.g., Cynewulf's *Andreas*, *Juliana*, and *Old English Elegies*) where 'hond' frequently appears in transliterations and translations denoting physical action—such as wielding shields in battle (\"rond ond hand on herefelda helm ealgodon\"), crafting (\"hond bith gelaered\"), or divine creation (\"fastened them firm with His own hands\")—and Urdu poetry (e.g., Allama Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara* and Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-e-Ghalib*) with occasional English translations using \"hand\" metaphorically (e.g., \"White Hand's miracle hidden up their sleeves\"),[^1][^2] there are no passages analyzing these words philosophically as symbols of agency or action, nor any cross-linguistic comparison.[^3]\n\nThe Old English instances often tie the hand to heroic agency in combat or labor,[^4] and Urdu examples evoke mystical or divine intervention,[^5] but the corpus lacks explicit thematic treatment or side-by-side analysis of 'dast' vs. 'hond' in this frame. Searches for distinctive phrases like \"dast\", \"hond\", \"hand agency\", or \"hand action\" yielded no conceptual discussions, only literal or poetic usages in narrative contexts.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 4, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/04-jinhein-main-dhoondta-tha-aasmanon-mein-zameenon-m/translation/#p-8efa1b).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, Ch. 1, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-868413).\n\n[^3]: Searches across the corpus (e.g., for \"hand\", \"hond\", \"dast\") confirmed no analytical content; results were narrative/poetic only.\n\n[^4]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, Ch. 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/01-fela-bith-on-foldan-forthgesynra-geongra-geofona-t/transliteration/#p-e7bdcb).\n\n[^5]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, Ch. 11, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/11-chashm-e-qaatil-humein-kyonkar-na-bhala-yaad-rahe/translation/#p-7cb148).",
